{% from "source-toggle.njk" import sourceToggle, jsxSource, endSource %}
{% from "strategy-toggle.njk" import strategyToggle %}

<h2>JSX Adapter</h2>
<p>
    The JSX Adapter enables authoring Web Everything components using JSX/TSX syntax while compiling to the same primitives as HTML.
    It provides full type safety and IDE support while maintaining interconvertibility with other formats.
</p>

<section class="section-card">
    <h3 id="authoring-model">Authoring model — a mirror of HTML, not React</h3>
    <p>
        Because the goal is to define <em>any</em> element as HTML or JSX and toggle <strong>losslessly</strong>, JSX here is a
        faithful, reversible <strong>mirror dialect</strong> of the canonical HTML adapter — deliberately <em>not</em> React. So
        <code>class</code> (never <code>className</code>), <code>for</code> (never <code>htmlFor</code>), events as <code>on:*</code>
        string behaviors, and directives as the literal <code>&lt;template is="…"&gt;</code> element. Toggle the example below
        between the two spellings of the same element tree:
    </p>

    {{ sourceToggle("user-card-mirror") }}
    {% highlight "html" %}
<user-card class="featured" name="Ada Lovelace" on:select="choose($event)">
  <span slot="title">Ada Lovelace</span>
  <ul role="list">
    <template is="for-each" items="@links" key="id">
      <li><a history-link="/profile">Profile</a></li>
    </template>
  </ul>
  <output bind-text="status"></output>
</user-card>
    {% endhighlight %}
    {{ jsxSource("user-card-mirror") }}
    {% highlight "tsx" %}
<user-card class="featured" name="Ada Lovelace" onselect={choose}>
  <span slot="title">Ada Lovelace</span>
  <ul role="list">
    <template is="for-each" items="@links" key="id">
      <li><a history-link="/profile">Profile</a></li>
    </template>
  </ul>
  <output bind-text="status" />
</user-card>
    {% endhighlight %}
    {{ endSource() }}

    <p style="margin-bottom: 0; font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
        <strong>Note:</strong> the full row-by-row correspondence is the mapping table below, specified in
        <code>reports/2026-06-03-jsx-adapter-feature-mapping.md</code>. How a component <em>updates over time</em> — binding,
        virtual DOM, fine-grained reactivity — is a separate axis, now a first-class standard: the
        <a href="/projects/webcomponents/#protocol-render-strategy">Render Strategy Protocol</a> (Web Components).
        Try the two spellings side by side in the <a href="/demos/jsx-adapter-demo.html">JSX Adapter Playground</a>.
    </p>
</section>

<section class="section-card">
    <h3 id="rendering-strategy">Rendering strategy — the second, orthogonal axis</h3>
    <p>
        The toggle above switches the <em>spelling</em> of one tree (Axis-1: HTML ⇄ JSX). This second
        toggle switches the <em>update machine</em> (Axis-2): the same element tree authored under each
        registered <a href="/projects/webcomponents/#protocol-render-strategy">render strategy</a>. JSX
        only spells the tree — it never owns reactivity; the strategy is resolved from
        <code>CustomRenderStrategyRegistry</code>, so this toggle's tabs come from that catalog, not a
        hardcoded list.
    </p>
    <p style="font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
        The author writes the <strong>declarative-static</strong> source once; the <strong>vdom</strong> pane
        is generated from it at build time by the cross-strategy <code>lift</code> compiler
        (<code>blocks/renderers/jsx/render-strategy/crossStrategy.ts</code>). Note how the directive
        <code>&lt;template is="for-each"&gt;</code> becomes a plain <code>.map()</code> — directives are an
        artifact of the declarative-static strategy, so they appear and disappear <em>with the strategy</em>.
    </p>
    {% set strategyExample %}
<template is="for-each" items="users" item="user" key="id"><li class="user-row">{{ '{{' }} user.name {{ '}}' }}</li></template>
    {% endset %}
    {{ strategyToggle("users-list-strategy", renderStrategies, strategyExample) }}
</section>

<section class="section-card">
    <h3 id="feature-mapping">Feature mapping — the contract</h3>
    <p>
        Each HTML-adapter construct has one JSX spelling of the <em>same</em> element tree. This is the reversible
        contract the <a href="/demos/jsx-adapter-demo.html">playground</a> and the build-time transform both conform to.
        Most rows are mechanical; the designed cells are events (5), directives (7–8), and interpolation (9).
    </p>
    <we-data-table><table>
        <thead>
            <tr><th>HTML adapter</th><th>JSX mirror</th><th>Round-trip</th><th>Notes</th></tr>
        </thead>
        <tbody>
            <tr><td><code>&lt;div class="x"&gt;</code></td><td><code>&lt;div class="x"&gt;</code></td><td>✅</td><td><code>class</code>, never <code>className</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>&lt;user-card name="Ana"&gt;</code></td><td><code>&lt;user-card name="Ana"&gt;</code></td><td>✅</td><td>custom element = string tag (no PascalCase rename)</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>&lt;input required&gt;</code></td><td><code>&lt;input required /&gt;</code></td><td>✅</td><td>bare boolean ⇄ <code>required={true}</code></td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>history-link="/x"</code></td><td>same kebab attrs</td><td>✅</td><td>behaviors are plain attributes</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>on:click="inc($event)"</code></td><td><code>onclick={inc}</code> <em>or</em> <code>on:click="inc($event)"</code></td><td>✅¹</td><td>¹reversible for <strong>named</strong> handlers; inline closures are one-way (lossy)</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>&lt;span slot="header"&gt;</code></td><td><code>&lt;span slot="header"&gt;</code></td><td>✅</td><td>named slots = <code>slot</code> attribute</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>&lt;template is="for-each" items="…" key="…"&gt;</code></td><td><code>&lt;template is="for-each" items="…" key="…"&gt;</code></td><td>✅</td><td>literal element form is canonical; <code>&lt;For&gt;</code>/<code>&lt;Show&gt;</code>/<code>&lt;Resource&gt;</code> sugar is an equivalent spelling (implemented)</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>&lt;!-- control:for-each … --&gt;</code></td><td><code>&lt;template is="for-each" …&gt;</code></td><td>⚠️</td><td>JSX can't carry semantic comments, so it canonicalizes on the element form</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>&#123;&#123; expr &#125;&#125;</code> / <code>[[ expr ]]</code> text</td><td>—</td><td>⛔</td><td>reactive text is <strong>Axis 2</strong> (reactive-by-path); not mapped here</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>bind-text="count"</code></td><td><code>bind-text="count"</code></td><td>✅</td><td>the Axis-1 reversible binding form</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>options="@countries"</code></td><td><code>options="@countries"</code></td><td>✅</td><td>injector/context refs are string-valued</td></tr>
            <tr><td><code>&lt;component name="…"&gt;</code></td><td><code>&lt;component name="…"&gt;</code></td><td>✅</td><td>declarative element passes through</td></tr>
        </tbody>
    </table></we-data-table>
</section>

<section class="section-card">
    <h3 id="design-principles">Design Principles</h3>
    <ul>
        <li><strong>Semantic Equivalence:</strong> Every JSX construct maps to the same HTML element tree (and most map back).</li>
        <li><strong>No Runtime Magic:</strong> JSX compiles to standard Web Everything primitives—no framework-specific runtime.</li>
        <li><strong>Type Safety:</strong> Full TypeScript support with typed props, events, and slots.</li>
        <li><strong>Reversible where it can be:</strong> the transform round-trips the mechanical rows and named handlers; inline closures, comment-form directives, and reactive <code>&#123;&#123; &#125;&#125;</code> text are <strong>lossy by design</strong> (see the mapping notes) and don't round-trip.</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section class="section-card">
    <h3 id="component-mapping">Component Definition</h3>
    <p>JSX provides the syntax for defining component templates within class-based Custom Elements:</p>

    {% highlight "tsx" %}
// Class-based Custom Element with JSX template
class UserCard extends HTMLElement {
    static observedAttributes = ['name', 'avatar'];

    connectedCallback() {
        this.attachShadow({ mode: 'open' });
        this.render();
    }

    attributeChangedCallback() {
        this.render();
    }

    render() {
        const name = this.getAttribute('name');
        const avatar = this.getAttribute('avatar');

        // JSX syntax for the template
        this.shadowRoot.replaceChildren(
            <div class="user-card">
                <img src={avatar} alt={name} />
                <span>{name}</span>
            </div>
        );
    }
}

customElements.define('user-card', UserCard);
    {% endhighlight %}

    <p style="margin-top: 1rem; font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
        <strong>Note:</strong> For functional component syntax, see the <a href="/adapters/functional-component-adapter/">Functional Component Adapter</a>—a separate adapter that compiles functions to class-based elements.
    </p>
</section>

<section class="section-card">
    <h3 id="directive-syntax">Directive Syntax</h3>
    <p>
        The canonical directive spelling is the literal <code>&lt;template is="…"&gt;</code> customized built-in —
        <strong>identical on both sides</strong>, because it is the one form JSX can both express and reverse. So a
        directive is authored the same way in HTML and JSX:
    </p>

    <h4 id="for-each-directive">For Each</h4>
    {% highlight "tsx" %}
// JSX — same element tree as HTML
<ul role="list">
    <template is="for-each" items="@links" key="id">
        <li><a history-link="/profile">Profile</a></li>
    </template>
</ul>

// HTML — identical
<ul role="list">
    <template is="for-each" items="@links" key="id">
        <li><a history-link="/profile">Profile</a></li>
    </template>
</ul>
    {% endhighlight %}

    <h4 id="conditional-directive">Conditionals</h4>
    {% highlight "tsx" %}
// Both HTML and JSX
<template is="if" condition="isVisible">
    <modal-dialog title="Hello"></modal-dialog>
</template>
    {% endhighlight %}

    <div class="callout" style="border-left: 3px solid var(--color-primary); padding: 0.5rem 0 0.5rem 1rem; margin-top: 1rem;">
        <p style="margin: 0 0 0.4rem 0;"><strong>Component sugar — <code>&lt;For&gt;</code> / <code>&lt;Show&gt;</code> / <code>&lt;Resource&gt;</code>.</strong></p>
        <p style="margin: 0; font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
            The prettier component spellings (<code>&lt;For each&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;Show when&gt;</code>, <code>&lt;Resource from&gt;</code>)
            are <strong>optional sugar</strong> that lower to and from the same <code>&lt;template is="…"&gt;</code> directive
            registry. They are now <strong>implemented</strong> — <code>desugar()</code> lowers them, <code>sugarize()</code> lifts the
            canonical form back, and the runtime <code>&lt;For&gt;</code>/<code>&lt;Show&gt;</code>/<code>&lt;Resource&gt;</code> components
            build the same DOM as the canonical directive. See the
            <a href="/demos/jsx-directive-sugar-demo.html">Directive Sugar Playground</a>. Both spellings are equivalent; the
            component layer is purely an alternative <em>spelling</em>, not a different runtime.
        </p>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="section-card">
    <h3 id="behaviors">Behaviors</h3>
    <p>Web Behaviors are applied as attributes with type-safe props:</p>

    {% highlight "tsx" %}
// JSX - Behaviors as typed attributes
<button
    history-link="/dashboard"
    click-outside={handleClose}
    trusted-html="sanitize"
>
    Navigate
</button>

// TypeScript definitions provide autocomplete
interface BehaviorAttributes {
    'history-link'?: string;
    'click-outside'?: () => void;
    'trusted-html'?: string;
    'trusted-html-strict'?: boolean;
}
    {% endhighlight %}
</section>

<section class="section-card">
    <h3 id="slots-projection">Slots &amp; Content Projection</h3>
    <p>Named slots work naturally with JSX children:</p>

    {% highlight "tsx" %}
// JSX — custom elements stay string tags; slots are the `slot` attribute (same tree as HTML)
<card-element>
    <span slot="header">Title</span>
    <div slot="body">Content here</div>
    <div slot="footer">
        <button>Action</button>
    </div>
</card-element>

// HTML — identical
<card-element>
    <span slot="header">Title</span>
    <div slot="body">Content here</div>
    <div slot="footer">
        <button>Action</button>
    </div>
</card-element>
    {% endhighlight %}
    <p style="margin: 0.75rem 0 0 0; font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
        The mirror dialect does <strong>not</strong> rename elements to PascalCase components
        (<code>&lt;Card&gt;</code>/<code>&lt;CardHeader&gt;</code>) — that would break round-trip. The element tree is the
        same on both sides; only the surrounding syntax differs.
    </p>
</section>

<section class="section-card">
    <h3 id="events">Event Handling</h3>
    <p>
        The <strong>canonical, reversible</strong> form is the <code>on:*</code> <em>string</em> behavior — it has an HTML
        representation, so it round-trips. JSX also accepts a <strong>function</strong> prop (<code>onclick={fn}</code>);
        a <em>named</em> reference round-trips (resolved through the injector handler context), but an inline closure
        <code>onclick={() =&gt; …}</code> has no string form and is <strong>one-way (lossy)</strong>.
    </p>

    {% highlight "tsx" %}
// JSX — canonical string form (round-trips), identical to HTML
<button on:click="inc($event)">Submit</button>

// JSX — function form: named ref round-trips, inline closure is lossy
<button onclick={inc}>Submit</button>           // ✅ reversible (named)
<button onclick={() => inc()}>Submit</button>   // ⛔ one-way (no HTML form)

// HTML — the canonical spelling
<button on:click="inc($event)">Submit</button>
    {% endhighlight %}
    <p style="margin: 0.75rem 0 0 0; font-size: 0.9rem; color: var(--color-text-muted);">
        Whether the playground <em>displays</em> events in string vs function form is a planned UI sub-toggle
        (<a href="/backlog/051-jsx-event-style-toggle/">jsx-event-style-toggle</a>).
    </p>
</section>

<section class="section-card">
    <h3 id="ast-transformation">The transform — built and running</h3>
    <p>
        The bidirectional transform is <strong>implemented and tested</strong>, not aspirational. Two small,
        DOM-impl-agnostic functions live in <code>blocks/renderers/jsx/</code> and run in the browser, in tests
        (happy-dom), and in the 11ty build (linkedom):
    </p>

    {% highlight "typescript" %}
import { htmlToJsx } from 'blocks/renderers/jsx/htmlToJsx';  // HTML → JSX (mirror dialect)
import { jsxToHtml } from 'blocks/renderers/jsx/jsxToHtml';  // JSX  → HTML (lean, regex-based)

// htmlToJsx walks nodeType/nodeName and takes an injectable document, so it is
// portable across DOM implementations:
const jsx = htmlToJsx(html, document);   // browser / happy-dom / linkedom

// jsxToHtml is the reverse spelling (no DOM needed):
const html = jsxToHtml(jsx);
    {% endhighlight %}

    <p style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">Where it already runs today:</p>
    <ul style="margin-bottom: 0;">
        <li><strong>Build-time source panes.</strong> The <code>autoToggle</code> macro authors HTML once and
            generates the JSX pane at build time via an 11ty <code>htmlToJsx</code> filter — see the
            <a href="/blocks/for-each/">for-each block page</a>.</li>
        <li><strong>The playground.</strong> The <a href="/demos/jsx-adapter-demo.html">JSX Adapter Playground</a>
            renders mirror-dialect examples live and shows <em>conformance</em> (JSX→DOM == canonical HTML) and
            <em>round-trip</em> (<code>htmlToJsx</code> ⇄ authored) badges, backed by CI.</li>
        <li><strong>Migrating &amp; exporting</strong> existing HTML ⇄ JSX across the format boundary, within the
            reversibility limits noted in the mapping table.</li>
    </ul>
</section>

<section class="section-card">
    <h3 id="wiring">Wiring into a project — the JSX runtime</h3>
    <p>
        An external project wires the adapter with the <strong>automatic</strong> JSX runtime — the native,
        per-file-free convention. Point the compiler's <code>jsxImportSource</code> at the published runtime
        package and it injects the factory import for you; nothing per-file, no <code>jsxFactory</code> pragma:
    </p>

    {% highlight "json" %}
// tsconfig.json — automatic runtime (the documented default for external projects)
{
  "compilerOptions": {
    "jsx": "react-jsx",
    "jsxImportSource": "@frontierui/jsx-runtime"
  }
}
    {% endhighlight %}

    <p style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
        The same one line works in esbuild / Vite (which read the field, or take it directly):
    </p>

    {% highlight "typescript" %}
// esbuild / Vite — automatic runtime
{ jsx: 'automatic', jsxImportSource: '@frontierui/jsx-runtime' }
    {% endhighlight %}

    <p>
        Install <code>@frontierui/jsx-runtime</code> and the compiler resolves <code>jsx</code>/<code>jsxs</code>
        from its <code>/jsx-runtime</code> export (and <code>/jsx-dev-runtime</code> in dev) automatically. The
        factory is the same one this page documents — JSX still lowers to standard DOM, no framework runtime.
    </p>

    <p style="margin-bottom: 0.5rem;">
        <strong>Classic is the in-repo / no-package fallback.</strong> Web&nbsp;Everything's own pages don't
        install the package — they wire the factory <em>classically</em>, injecting it from the local source so
        there's no bare-specifier to resolve:
    </p>

    {% highlight "typescript" %}
// vite.config — classic, our in-repo wiring (no package install)
esbuild: {
  jsxFactory: 'jsx.createElement',
  jsxFragment: 'jsx.Fragment',
  jsxInject: `import jsx from 'blocks/renderers/jsx/JSXRenderer'`,
}
    {% endhighlight %}

    <p style="margin: 0;">
        Both produce identical DOM — <code>automatic</code> is the default we document for consumers (one
        config line, real install), <code>classic</code> is the fallback when there's no package to install
        (our repo, or a vendored copy). See <a href="/backlog/126-jsx-runtime-documented-default/">#126</a> for the ruling.
    </p>
</section>

